modules.description: This module defines a variant type for timestamp precisions used in InfluxDB, including nanoseconds to hours. It provides conversions between these precision values and their string representations in the InfluxDB line protocol. Use this module when specifying or parsing timestamp precisions in InfluxDB write or query operations.

This module defines a key-value pair structure for representing data fields in InfluxDB points, supporting float, integer, string, and boolean values. It provides functions to construct fields of each type, optionally specifying a name, and includes utilities to serialize fields to strings according to the InfluxDB line protocol. Typical use cases include building and formatting metric data for time series storage or API submission.

Builds and parses HTTP headers for InfluxDB API requests. Handles version negotiation and constructs ping responses with build and version metadata. Useful for validating server connections and retrieving service metadata.

This module defines a data structure for representing time series data points with a name, fields, tags, and an optional timestamp. It provides functions to construct points with customizable tags, fields, and timestamps, and to serialize them into the InfluxDB line protocol format. It is used to prepare data for writing to an InfluxDB database, ensuring correct formatting and structure.

This module defines a type `t` as an `int64` representing a UNIX timestamp with nanosecond precision. It includes functions to convert a float in seconds to a timestamp and to format a timestamp as a string truncated to a specified precision. Use this module when working with time values in InfluxDB line protocol, especially when precise time formatting or conversion from floating-point seconds is required.

This module handles the core data structures and utilities for interacting with InfluxDB, focusing on time series data construction, serialization, and API communication. It centers around timestamps with nanosecond precision, key-value fields supporting multiple types, and structured data points with tags and optional timestamps. You can use it to format metrics for storage, construct valid InfluxDB line protocol entries, and manage API headers for server interaction. For example, you can build a time series point with custom tags and fields, convert a floating-point timestamp to nanoseconds, or generate HTTP headers for an InfluxDB API request.
